[1
Date: Thu, 15 Mar 2001 16:41:38
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: ABC news, 3/15/01 [edited
<http://abcnews.go.com/wire/World/reuters20010315_1801.html>

Jamaica imposed strict new rules on international airline passengers to
protect the Caribbean island's cattle herd from foot-and-mouth disease
inadvertently carried into the country by tourists, a Ministry of
Agriculture official said. Passengers arriving from Britain at Jamaica's 2
international airports -- Norman Manley International in Kingston and
Sangster International in the tourist mecca of Montego Bay -- must wipe
their feet on a carpet soaked in disinfectant, Dr. Cedric Lazarus, senior
veterinary scientist at the Ministry of Agriculture, said Wednesday.
More than 100 international flights arrive in Jamaica daily, including a
few directly from London, the Airports Authority said. Foot-and-mouth
disease last broke out in Jamaica in the 1920s, originating in cattle that
were imported from India to upgrade the local stock, Lazarus said. The
disease was eradicated within a year after that outbreak.
