Date: Thu 15 Mar 2001 09:38:36
From: Padmanabhan Badrinath <badrishanthi@hotmail.com>
Source : Gulf News 15 Mar 2001 [edited

The UAE has tightened restrictions on the import of live animals following
the discovery of 8 cases of foot and mouth disease. The cases were found
among imported calves, the origin of which is not known. Nor is it known if
the calves were in one or more of the 7 emirates [that make up the UAE.
The country's Minister of Agriculture and Fisheries, Saeed Mohammed Al
Raqabani, told the Arabic daily newspaper Al Khaleej that the necessary
precautions to prevent the spread of foot and mouth disease in the country
had been taken.
Earlier, the Sharjah-based Al Khaleej quoted the Minister as saying that he
had issued a decree banning all imports of animals and birds without prior
permission from the Ministry.
Last month, the Ministry banned all imports of British livestock as well as
dairy products following the outbreak of foot and mouth in Britain. Qasim
Sultan, Director General of the Dubai Municipality, said that Dubai is free
from foot and mouth disease.
In a statement, Qasim Sultan said that the Dubai Municipality wants to
reassure everybody that the city is free from any animal or meat affected
by the disease and that the municipality had taken stringent preventive
measures to ensure that no animal from the countries infected by the
disease pass through its ports of entry.
