[5
Date: Thu 15 Mar 2001 11:50:45
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Khaleej Times, 15 Mar 2001 [edited
<http://www.khaleejtimes.com/middleeast.htm>

Gulf Arab states have launched measures to prevent the spread of
foot-and-mouth disease in the region, where Saudi Arabia and the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) reported 10 cases in cows, officials said on Thursday.
Ali Arab, head of the livestock department at the UAE's Agriculture
Ministry, told Reuters 8 infected cows have been killed and a quarantine
imposed on farms where they were found. "The UAE is now free of
foot-and-mouth disease," he said, denying media reports on Thursday of more
cases. Al-Ittihad daily reported 14 cases in the oasis town of Al-Ain,
including 13 on one farm, but it was not clear if the figure includes the 8
reported by the government. Other papers reported one more case on the
eastern coast.
"Coordination was launched among the Gulf Arab states to take all measures
to ensure that the disease does not spread in the region," Arab said. All
imported livestock would be inspected and disinfected at all ports, and
imports now require prior approval, he added. The Gulf Arab states of Saudi
Arabia, the UAE, Oman, Kuwait, Bahrain and Qatar import most of their meat
and livestock. They have banned imports of meat and livestock from Britain,
other European countries and some African and Arab states. Oman and Kuwait
said this week they had no foot-and-mouth cases. In Saudi Arabia, where 2
cases were reported, al-Eqtisadiah newspaper on Thursday said one more case
was found. The Saudi Commerce Ministry on Wednesday banned imports of all
meat and meat products from Iran, India and Taiwan. A senior UAE quarantine
official said tough measures already in place would eliminate any risk from
the viral disease at the $6-million Dubai World Cup horse race on 24 Mar 2001.
